ANC secretary general Gwede Mantashe said on Tuesday that&nbsp;the ruling party&#8217;s national executive committee (NEC) did not accept the call for President Jacob Zuma to step down as the party&#8217;s president. BREAKING NEWS: #ANCNEC Gwede Mantashe says NEC didn&#8217;t accept the call for president to step down. &mdash; Mail &amp; Guardian (@mailandguardian) November 29, 2016 Mantashe was speaking at Luthuli house during the ANC&#8217;s media briefing on the outcomes of the NEC meeting which was held in Irene, outside Tshwane, at the weekend and ended on Monday.&nbsp; The City Press&nbsp;newspaper reported on Sunday that&nbsp;Tourism Minister Derek Hanekom tabled a motion for the president to step down in the ANC NEC meeting on Saturday. &#8220;The NEC did not support the call for the president to step down,&#8221; Mantashe said.&nbsp; &#8220;This issue was debated openly, robustly and, as we said, sometimes it was very difficult for members themselves.&#8221; Mantashe: Issue was debated openly robustly and sometimes very difficult for members themselves. More important to work towards unity of ANC &mdash; Mail &amp; Guardian (@MG_Reporter) November 29, 2016